{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17509299","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17509299"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:16:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:16:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11415"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11415","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11415"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.04,0.09,0.72,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4051"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92938"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4051","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4051"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11415"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76291"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1925"},{"type":"tags","id":"2602"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"10964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4656"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31892"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42598"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92938","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92938"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 75-year-old man presents with a five-month history of progressively worsening dyspnoea, reduced exercise tolerance and bilateral ankle swelling. He has trouble laying flat and now requires the use of three pillows to get to sleep. His medical history include a myocardial infarction at the age of 69, hypertension, depression and type 2 diabetes mellitus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPhysical examination reveals bibasal inspiratory crackles and a JVP visible at 5cm vertical height above the sternal angle. An echocardiogram is performed revealing a left ventricular ejection fraction (LVEF) of 34%.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"In the management of heart failure with reduced ejection fraction (HFrEF), all of the following treatment options have been shown to reduce mortality EXCEPT?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Controlled-release metoprolol","Enalapril","Spironolactone","Digoxin","Sacubitril/valsartan"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDigoxin\u003C/strong\u003E \u2013 Digoxin is a treatment option that is reserved for patients in sinus rhythm with HFrEF who remain symptomatic despite established medical therapy (such as with ACE-I and beta-blockers). Whilst it has been shown to reduce the risk of hospitalisation (both overall and for worsening heart failure) no mortality benefit has been demonstrated (The Digitalis Investigation Group, 1997).\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EControlled-release metoprolol\u003C/strong\u003E \u2013 A reduction in total mortality with the use of controlled-released metoprolol in heart failure has been demonstrated in the MERIT-HF study (2000).\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnalapril\u003C/strong\u003E \u2013 A reduction in mortality has been demonstrated with the use of enalapril in patients with chronic heart failure and ejection fractions \u226435% in the SOLVD study (1991).\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003ESpironolactone\u003C/strong\u003E \u2013 Mineralcorticoid receptor antagonists are recommended in patients who remain symptomatic despite treatment with an ACE-I and a beta-blocker and with LVEF \u226435%. Spironolactone has been shown in the Randomized Aldactone Evaluation Study (1999) to reduce the risk of both morbidity and death among patients with severe heart failure (in addition to standard therapy).\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003ESacubitril/valsartan\u003C/strong\u003E \u2013 Sacubitril/valsartan has been shown to be superior to enalapril in reducing the risk of death and of hospitalization for heart failure with LVEF \u226440% in the PARADIGM-HF trial (2014).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The role of digoxin in HFrEF is limited to patients with persistent NYHA functional class III to IV symptoms despite initiation of initial optimal medical therapy.","There is no evidence that digoxin improves mortality in HFrEF."],"references":["The Digitalis Investigation Group 1997, \u0027The Effect of Digoxin on Mortality and Morbidity in Patients with Heart Failure\u0027, New England Journal of Medicine, vol. 336, no. 8, pp. 525-533.","Hjalmarson, A, Goldstein, S, Fagerberg, B, et al. Effects of controlled-release metoprolol on total mortality, hospitalizations, and well-being in patients with heart failure: the Metoprolol CR/XL Randomized Intervention Trial in congestive heart failure (MERIT-HF). MERIT-HF Study Group. JAMA, vol. 283, no. 10, Mar 08, pp. 1295-1302.","Yusuf, S, Pitt, B, Davis, CE, et al. 1991, Effect of enalapril on survival in patients with reduced left ventricular ejection fractions and congestive heart failure. N Engl J Med, vol. 325, no. 5, Aug 01, pp. 293-302.","Pitt, B, Zannad, F, Remme, WJ, et al 1999, The effect of spironolactone on morbidity and mortality in patients with severe heart failure. Randomized Aldactone Evaluation Study Investigators. N Engl J Med, vol. 341, no. 10, Sep 02, pp. 709-717.","McMurray, JJV, Packer, M, Desai, AS, et al. 2014, Angiotensin\u2013Neprilysin Inhibition versus Enalapril in Heart Failure. New England Journal of Medicine, vol. 371, no. 11, pp. 993-1004."]},"relationships":{"itemRevi